  "prompt": "Can you get pregnant without cervical mucus?",
  "response": "Cervical mucus plays a crucial role in fertility by creating a hospitable environment for sperm, helping them travel through the cervix and into the uterus to reach an egg. However, **it is still possible to get pregnant without noticeable cervical mucus**, though the chances may be lower.\n\n### Here\u2019s why:\n1. **Cervical mucus may still be present**: Even if you don\u2019t notice it, your body might still produce small amounts of cervical mucus that can facilitate sperm movement.\n2. **Sperm survival**: Sperm can survive for up to 5 days in the female reproductive tract, so ovulation timing is more critical than the presence of cervical mucus.\n3. **Other factors**: Fertility depends on many factors, such as ovulation, sperm quality, and overall reproductive health, not just cervical mucus.\n\nThat said, the absence of cervical mucus can sometimes indicate underlying issues (e.g., hormonal imbalances, dehydration, or certain medications) that might affect fertility. If you're trying to conceive and notice a lack of cervical mucus, consulting a healthcare provider can help identify and address any potential concerns.",
